The changes to its electoral code come a few months before presidential elections are due to take place. The diaspora’s right to vote has been one of the opposition’s demands. Following Tuesday's vote, members of the ruling coalition said everything was on track for next year’s election. However, some opposition members, including two candidates in next year’s election, abstained from voting. A number of protests in recent years over the electoral process have been violently suppressed by security forces. President Faure Gnassingbé took power in 2005 after succeeding his father. Earlier this year, Togo’s parliament approved a change to its constitution allowing him to run two more times and potentially remain in office until 2030.

--BBC--